  1. Calculate the empirical trend in your data using ordinary least squares. Also calculate the expected variance in your estimator using standard methods that assume independence of the data points.
##if using y=ax+b, a is the record index, then the a is the empirical trend we are looking for, according to OLS, a=cov(x,y)/var(x)
index=seq(1,100,1)
index=index-mean(index)
COV<- function(x,y) {
  if(length(x)!=length(y)) {stop('x must have the same length as y ')}
  x.bar <- mean(x)
  y.bar <- mean(y)
  N <- length(x)
  Cov <- (sum((x-x.bar)*(y-y.bar))) / (N-1)
  return(Cov)
}
##Calculate trend, named a
a <- COV(index,ar1)/var(index)
##Calculate the other parameter in OLS, named b, then y=ax+b

###lag-1 autocorrelation coefficient###
xminus <- ar1[1:99]
xplus <- ar1[2:100]
r1 <- sum((xminus-mean(xminus))*(xplus-mean(xplus)))/((sqrt(sum((xminus-mean(xminus))^2)))*(sqrt(sum((xminus-mean(xminus))^2))))
n1 <- n*(1-r1)/(1+r1)
expon <- 2/3*(1-n1/n) ###Now the Wilks 5.36 becomes L=(101-L)^(expon)
fL <- function(L,expon){
  n=100
  result <- L-(n-L+1)^expon
  return(result)
}
##Check the approximate location of root of fL##
L=seq(-100,100,0.1)
plot(L-(n-L+1)^expon,type='l') ##see whether this interval contains root, the result is "yes"

eps=1e-7
max=max(L)
min=min(L)
tmp=0.5*(max+min)
check <- fL(tmp,expon)
while(abs(check)>eps){
  if(check<0){
    min=tmp
    tmp=0.5*(max+min)
  }else{
    max=tmp
    tmp=0.5*(max+min)
  }    
  check <- fL(tmp,expon)
}

###block bootstrap for 10000 times without overlap###
nblock <- floor(100/L)
stdp <- sample(1:100,10000,replace=T)
trends=rep(0,10000)
for(i in 1:10000){
  newar=rep(0,100)
  newar[1:(100-stdp[i]+1)]=ar1[stdp[i]:100]
  newar[(100-stdp[i]+2):100]=ar1[1:(stdp[i]-1)]
  sel=sample(1:nblock,nblock,replace=T)
  boot=rep(0,100)
  for(j in 1:nblock){
    boot[((j-1)*L+1):(j*L)]=newar[((sel[j]-1)*L+1):(sel[j]*L)]
  }
  sel=sample(1:nblock,1)

      boot[(j*L+1):100]=newar[((sel-1)*L+1):((sel-1)*L+1+100-j*L-1)]

getMAM <- function(index){
  tmp=index[which((index[,2]==3)|(index[,2]==4)|(index[,2]==5)),]
  l=length(unique(tmp[,1]))-1
  out=rep(0,l)
  for(i in 1:l){
    out[i]=mean(tmp[which(tmp[,1]==unique(tmp[,1])[i+1]),3])
  }
  out1 <- cbind(unique(tmp[,1])[2:(l+1)],out)
  return(out1)
}
getSON <- function(index){
  index=index[which(index[,3]!=-999.9),]
  tmp=index[which((index[,2]==9)|(index[,2]==10)|(index[,2]==11)),]
  l=length(unique(tmp[,1]))-1
  out=rep(0,l)
  for(i in 1:l){
    out[i]=mean(tmp[which(tmp[,1]==unique(tmp[,1])[i]),3])
  }
  out1 <- cbind(unique(tmp[,1])[2:(l+1)],out)
  return(out1)
}

###Add MAM average Tmin, MAM average Tmax in Los Angeles to CDD predictor, and SON average Tmin, SON average Tmax in Los Angeles to HDD predictor
getMAM <- function(index){
  tmp=index[which((index[,2]==3)|(index[,2]==4)|(index[,2]==5)),]
  l=length(unique(tmp[,1]))
  out=rep(0,l)
  for(i in 1:l){
    out[i]=mean(tmp[which(tmp[,1]==unique(tmp[,1])[i]),3])
  }
  out1 <- cbind(unique(tmp[,1]),out)
  return(out1)
}
getSON <- function(index){
  index=index[which(index[,3]!=-999.9),]
  tmp=index[which((index[,2]==9)|(index[,2]==10)|(index[,2]==11)),]
  l=length(unique(tmp[,1]))-1
  out=rep(0,l)
  for(i in 1:l){
    out[i]=mean(tmp[which(tmp[,1]==unique(tmp[,1])[i]),3])
  }
  out1 <- cbind(unique(tmp[,1])[2:(l+1)],out)
  return(out1)
}

  1. End with a short write up of results, explaining what you found and if your model should be used by the energy trading desk. According to results from question (d), the models cannot capture the variance of the original time series very well, the estimated values using the training dataset are confined within a small range, while the real time series has much larger variance, probably because non of the predictor time series can provide the same magnitude of variance as the HDD and CDD time series (see results in question (a)). A comparison of the parameter variance shows that the parameter with the largest variance is usually interception, this is understandable because the predictors have small variance, the variance of the real time series can hardly be explained by any of the predictors except the interception. However, this expression of variance in the model is not true, and leads to results that the models yield bad predictions for 2006-2018 HDD and CDD values – the model either cannot capture the value’s variation or the uncertainty of the predicted time series is so large that we cannot even draw any conclusions of prediction with confidence from the models’ results. Therefore, this model shouldn’t be used by the energy trading desk. However, if we do not estimate the HDD and CDD directly, instead estimate the standardized anomaly of HDD and CDD based on a certain constant level, the models we build may be able to do a better job, since the variance difference between the anomalies and the climate indices might be smaller.
